style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;">Beneficial conversion feature</font><font style="display: inline;"> &#x2014; The issuance of our Series A Preferred Stock generated a beneficial conversion feature, which arises when a debt or equity security is issued with an embedded conversion option that is beneficial to the investor or in the money at inception because the conversion option has an effective strike price that is less than the market price of the underlying stock at the commitment date. We recognized the beneficial conversion feature by allocating the intrinsic value of the conversion option, which is the number of shares of common stock available upon conversion multiplied by the difference between the effective conversion price per share and the fair value of common stock per share on the commitment date, to additional paid-in capital, resulting in a discount on the Series A Preferred Stock. We are accreting the discount over </font><font style="display: inline;">eight</font><font style="display: inline;"> years from the date of issuance through the redemption date. The first complaint was filed in November 2007 and several other complaints were filed shortly thereafter. These actions were consolidated and, in September 2008, the district court appointed a lead plaintiff and counsel. An amended consolidated complaint was filed in December 2008. The amended complaint purported to state claims under Sections&nbsp;10(b), 20(a), and 20A of the Exchange Act on behalf of a class of all persons who purchased our common stock between April&nbsp;2, 2007 and April&nbsp;14, 2008 (the "Class Period"). The amended complaint also added our independent auditor as a defendant. The amended complaint alleged that, during the Class Period, the defendants made false and misleading public statements about us and our business and prospects and, as a result, the market price of our common stock was artificially inflated. The amended complaint also claimed that certain current and former officers and directors traded in our common stock on the basis of material non-public information. The amended complaint sought compensatory damages on behalf of the alleged class in an unspecified amount, including interest, and also sought attorneys' fees and costs of litigation. On February&nbsp;28, 2011, the District Court granted motions to dismiss filed by the defendants and dismissed all claims. A final judgment was thereafter entered. Plaintiffs subsequently appealed to the United States Court of Appeals for the Tenth Circuit. We and those current and former officers and directors named as defendants entered into a Stipulation of Settlement with the plaintiffs to resolve all claims asserted against us by the plaintiffs on behalf of the putative class. Our independent auditor was not a party to the Stipulation of Settlement. The Stipulation of Settlement received preliminary approval from the District Court on August&nbsp;28, 2013. On September 18, 2014, the District Court entered an order of final approval of the settlement and, on September 19, 2014, the District Court entered final judgment dismissing the action against us and those current and former officers and directors named as defendants in its entirety</font><font style="display: inline;"> with prejudice. </font><font style="display: inline;">The full settlement amount </font><font style="display: inline;">has been paid by our insurers. </font><font style="display: inline;">Since no notice of appeal was filed during the appeal period, this action is now terminated as to Crocs a</font><font style="display: inline;">nd its affiliated individuals. </font><font style="display: inline;">Crocs considers this matter closed.</font> </p> <p 280000000 22000000 0.08 0.05 0.05 0.460 P8Y 1.01 1.00 P8Y 35500000 1100000 12400000 3500000 <div> <div style="margin-left:0pt;margin-right:0pt;"> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;">Recently Issued Accounting Pronouncements</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-style:italic;text-decoration:underline;">Going Concern</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 12pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:12pt;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">On August 27, 2014, the FASB issued ASU 2014-15, which provides guidance on determining when and how reporting entities must disclose going concern uncertainties in their financial statements. The new standard requires management to perform interim and annual assessments of an entity&#x2019;s ability to continue as a going concern within one year of the date of issuance of the entity&#x2019;s financial statements (or within one year after the date on which the financial statements are available to be issued, when applicable). Further, an entity must provide certain disclosures if there is &#x201C;substantial doubt about the entity&#x2019;s ability to continue as a going concern.&#x201D;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">The FASB believes that requiring management to perform the assessment will enhance the timeliness, clarity and consistency of related disclosures and improve convergence with IFRSs (which emphasize management&#x2019;s responsibility for performing the going concern assessment). However, the time horizon for the assessment (look-forward period) and the disclosure thresholds under U.S. GAAP and IFRSs will continue to differ. This ASU is effective for annual periods ending after December 16, 2016, and interim periods thereafter; early adoption is permitted. The Company does not believe that this pronouncement will have a material impact </font><font style="display: inline;">on our financial statement disclosures.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-style:italic;text-decoration:underline;">Share-Based Payment</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 12pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:12pt;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">On June 19, 2014, the FASB issued ASU 2014-12 in response to the EITF consensus on Issue 13-D. The ASU clarifies that entities should treat performance targets that can be met after the requisite service period of a share-based payment award as performance conditions that affect vesting. Therefore, an entity would not record compensation expense related to an award for which transfer to the employee is contingent on the entity&#x2019;s satisfaction of a performance target until it becomes probable that the performance target will be met. The ASU does not contain any new disclosure requirements. This ASU is effective for all entities for reporting periods (including interim periods) beginning after December 15, 2015. The Company does not believe that this pronouncement will have a material impact to the Company&#x2019;s consolidated financial statements.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-style:italic;text-decoration:underline;">Revenue Recognition</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 12pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:12pt;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">In May 2014, the FASB issued their final standard on revenue from contracts with customers. The standard, issued as ASU No. 2014-09: </font><font style="display: inline;font-style:italic;">Revenue from Contracts with Customers (Topic 606)</font><font style="display: inline;"> by the FASB, outlines a single comprehensive model for entities to use in accounting for revenue arising from contracts with customers and supersedes most current revenue recognition guidance, including industry-specific guidance. The core principle of the revenue model is that &#x201C;an entity recognizes revenue to depict the transfer of promised goods or services to customers in an amount that reflects the consideration to which the entity expects to be entitled in exchange for those goods or services.&#x201D; In applying the revenue model to contracts within its scope, an entity:</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt;text-indent: -18pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-family:Symbol;">&#xF0B7;</font><font style="display: inline;"> Identifies the contract(s) with a customer (Step 1)</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt;text-indent: -18pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-family:Symbol;">&#xF0B7;</font><font style="display: inline;"> Identifies the performance obligations in the contract (Step 2)</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt;text-indent: -18pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-family:Symbol;">&#xF0B7;</font><font style="display: inline;"> Determines the transaction price (Step 3)</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt;text-indent: -18pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-family:Symbol;">&#xF0B7;</font><font style="display: inline;"> Allocates the transaction price to the performance obligations in the contract (Step 4)</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt;text-indent: -18pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-family:Symbol;">&#xF0B7;</font><font style="display: inline;"> Recognizes revenue when (or as) the entity satisfies a performance obligation (Step 5)</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">The ASU applies to all contracts with customers except those that are within the scope of other topics in the FASB Accounting Standards Codification. Certain of the ASU&#x2019;s provisions also apply to transfers of nonfinancial assets, including in-substance nonfinancial assets that are not an output of an entity&#x2019;s ordinary activities (e.g., sales of property, plant, and equipment, real estate or intangible assets). Existing accounting guidance applicable to these transfers has been amended or superseded. Compared with current U.S. GAAP, the ASU also requires significantly expanded disclosures about revenue recognition.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">The ASU is effective for annual reporting periods (including interim reporting periods within those periods) beginning after December 15, 2016. Early application is not permitted. The Company is currently evaluating the impact that this pronouncement will have on the Company&#x2019;s consolidated financial statements.</font> </p> <p><font size="1"> </font></p> </div> </div> SERIES A PREFERRED STOCK</font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;">On January&nbsp;27, 2014, we issued to </font><font style="display: inline;">Blackstone, together with </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;">the Blackstone Purchasers, </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;">200,000</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;"> shares</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;"> of our Series A Preferred Stock for an aggregate purchase price of </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;">$198.0</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;">&nbsp;million, or </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;">$990</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;"> per share, pursuant to an Investment Agreement between us and Blackstone, dated December&nbsp;28, 2013 (as amended, the &#x201C;Investment Agreement&#x201D;). In connection with the issuance of the Series A Preferred Stock (the &#x201C;Closing&#x201D;), we received proceeds of </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;">$182.2</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;"> million after deducting the issuance discount of </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;">$2.0</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;"> million and direct and incremental expenses of </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;">$15.8</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;"> million including financial advisory fees, closing costs, legal expenses and other offering-related expenses.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;font-size:10pt;">Participation Rights and Dividends</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;">The Series A Preferred Stock ranks senior to our common stock with respect to dividend rights and rights on liquidation, winding-up and dissolution. The Series A Preferred Stock has a stated value of </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;">$1,000</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;"> per share, and holders of Series A Preferred Stock are entitled to cumulative dividends payable quarterly in cash at a rate of </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;">6%</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;"> per annum. If we fail to make timely dividend payments, the dividend rate will increase to </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;">8%</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;"> per annum until such time as all accrued but unpaid dividends have been paid in full. Holders of Series A Preferred Stock are entitled to receive dividends declared or paid on our common stock and are entitled to vote together with the holders of our common stock as a single class, in </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;">each case, on an as-converted basis. As of December 31, 2014, we have accrued dividends of $</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;">3.1</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;"> million on the consolidated balance sheets, which were paid in cash to </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;">holders of the Series A Preferred Stock</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;"> on January 2, 2015. Holders of Series A Preferred Stock have certain limited special approval rights, including with respect to the issuance of </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-style:italic;font-size:10pt;">pari passu</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;"> or senior equity securities of the Company.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;font-size:10pt;">Conversion Features</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 12pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;">The Series A Preferred Stock is convertible at the option of the holders at any time after the Closing into shares of common stock at an implied conversion price of </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;">$14.50</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;"> per share, subject to adjustment. At our election, all or a portion of the Series A Preferred Stock will be convertible into the relevant number of shares of common stock on or after the third anniversary of the Closing, if the closing price of the common stock equals or exceeds </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;">$29.00</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;"> for </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;">20</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;"> consecutive trading days. inline;font-size:3pt;"></font><font style="display: inline;font-size:9pt;">The amounts in Other consist of various accrued expenses and </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:9pt;"> of the total balance as of December 31, 2014 or 2013.</font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;">Asset Retirement Obligations</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">We record a liability equal to the fair value of the estimated future cost to retire an asset, if the liability&#x2019;s fair value can be reasonably estimated. Our asset retirement obligation (&#x201C;ARO&#x201D;) liabilities are primarily associated with the disposal of property and equipment which we are contractually obligated to remove at the end of certain retail and office leases in order to restore the facilities back original condition as specified in the related lease agreements. We estimate the fair value of these liabilities based on current store closing costs and discount the costs back as if they were to be performed at the inception of the lease. At the inception of such leases, we record the ARO as a liability and also record a related asset in an amount equal to the estimated fair value of the obligation. The capitalized asset is then depreciated on a straight-line basis over the useful life of the asset. Upon retirement of the ARO liability, any difference between the actual retirement costs incurred and the previously recorded estimated ARO liability is recognized as a gain or loss in the consolidated statements of operations.</font><font style="display: inline;"> Our ARO liability as of </font><font style="display: inline;">December 31, 201</font><font style="display: inline;">4</font><font style="display: inline;"> and 201</font><font style="display: inline;">3</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;">was $</font><font style="display: inline;">2.2 </font><font style="display: inline;">million</font><font style="display: inline;"> and</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;">$</font><font style="display: inline;">2.0</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;million,</font><font style="display: inline;"> respectively.</font> </p> <p><font size="1"> </font></p> </div> </div> 57450000 42923000 104405000 101217000 15992000 9078000 36616000 8843000 97111000 80216000 14128000 16212000 12198000 9675000 98151000 99799000 14652000 -18352000 321532000 345732000 <div> <div style="margin-left:0pt;margin-right:0pt;"> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;">Advertising</font><font style="display: inline;">&#x2014;Advertising costs are expensed as incurred and production costs </font><font style="display: inline;">are </font><font style="display: inline;">expensed when the advertising is first run. 1400000 1000000 2000000 1410000 10949000 6600000 8827000 2000000 2200000 <div> <div style="margin-left:0pt;margin-right:0pt;"> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">We record a liability equal to the fair value of the estimated future cost to retire an asset, if the liability&#x2019;s fair value can be reasonably estimated. Our asset retirement obligation (&#x201C;ARO&#x201D;) liabilities are primarily associated with the disposal of property and equipment which we are contractually obligated to remove at the end of certain retail and office leases in order to restore the facilities back original condition as specified in the related lease agreements. We estimate the fair value of these liabilities based on current store closing costs and discount the costs back as if they were to be performed at the inception of the lease. At the inception of such leases, we record the ARO as a liability and also record a related asset in an amount equal to the estimated fair value of the obligation. The capitalized asset is then depreciated on a straight-line basis over the useful life of the asset. Upon retirement of the ARO liability, any difference between the actual retirement costs incurred and the previously recorded estimated ARO liability is recognized as a gain or loss in the consolidated statements of operations.</font> </p> <p><font size="1"> </font></p> </div> </div> 875159000 806931000 640077000 14093000 63743000 506054000 51155000 139855000 177343000 137701000 595408000 18132000 27337000 494272000 34032000 127077000 166878000 166285000 4251000 2368000 2165000 771000 200000 200000 257587000 294348000 317144000 267512000 36761000 22796000 -49632000 <div> <div style="margin-left:0pt;margin-right:0pt;"> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;">Cash and Cash Equivalents</font><font style="display: inline;">&#x2014;Cash and cash equivalents represent cash and short-term, highly liquid investments with maturities of three months or less at the date of purchase. The consolidated financial statements include the accounts of our wholly-owned subsidiaries as well as variable interest entities (&#x201C;VIE&#x201D;) for which we are the primary beneficiary after the elimination of intercompany accounts and transactions. The primary beneficiary of a VIE is the entity that has (i) the power to direct the activities of the VIE that most significantly impact the VIE&#x2019;s economic performance and (ii) the obligation to absorb losses of the VIE that could potentially be significant to the VIE or the right to receive benefits from the VIE that could potentially be significant to the VIE. </font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">In April 2011, we and an unrelated third party formed Crocs Gulf, LLC (&#x201C;Crocs Gulf&#x201D;) for the purpose of selling our products in the United Arab Emirates. Borrowings under the Credit Agreement are secured by all of our assets including all receivables, equipment, general intangibles, inventory, investment property, subsidiary stock and intellectual property. Borrowings under the Credit Agreement bear interest at a variable rate</font><font style="display: inline;">. For domestic rate loans, the interest rate is equal to the highest of (i) the daily federal funds open rate as quoted by ICAP North America, Inc. plus </font><font style="display: inline;">0.5%</font><font style="display: inline;">, (ii) PNC's prime rate and (iii) a daily LIBOR rate plus </font><font style="display: inline;">1.0%</font><font style="display: inline;">, in each case there is an additional margin ranging from </font><font style="display: inline;">0.25%</font><font style="display: inline;"> to </font><font style="display: inline;">1.00%</font><font style="display: inline;"> based on certain conditions. For LIBOR rate loans, the interest rate is equal to a LIBOR rate plus a margin ranging from </font><font style="display: inline;">1.25%</font><font style="display: inline;"> to </font><font style="display: inline;">2.00%</font><font style="display: inline;"> based on certain conditions. The Credit Agreement requires monthly interest payments with respect to domestic rate loans and at the end of each interest period with respect to LIBOR rate loans. The Credit Agreement further provides for a limit on the issuance of letters of credit to a maximum </font><font style="display: inline;">of </font><font style="display: inline;">$20.0</font><font style="display: inline;"> million</font><font style="display: inline;">. The Credit Agreement contains provisions requiring us to maintain compliance with certain restrictive and financial covenants. </font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">As of December 31, 2014 and 2013, we had </font><font style="display: inline;">no</font><font style="display: inline;"> outstanding borrowings under the Credit Agreement. As of December 31, 2014 and 2013, we had issued and outstanding letters of credit of </font><font style="display: inline;">$1.8</font><font style="display: inline;"> million and </font><font style="display: inline;">$7.2</font><font style="display: inline;"> million, respectively, which were reserved against the borrowing base under the terms of the Credit Agreement. During the years ended December 31, 2014, 2013 and 2012, we capitalized </font><font style="display: inline;">$0.1</font><font style="display: inline;"> million, </font><font style="display: inline;">$0.1</font><font style="display: inline;"> million and </font><font style="display: inline;">$0.5</font><font style="display: inline;"> million, respectively, in fees and third party costs which were incurred in connection with the Credit Agreement, as deferred financing</font><font style="display: inline;"> costs. </font><font style="display: inline;">As of December 31, 2014, we were in compliance with all restrictive financial and other covenants under the Credit Agreement. </font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;">Long-term Bank Borrowings</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">On December 10, 2012, we entered into a Master Installment Payment Agreement (&#x201C;Master IPA&#x201D;) with PNC in which PNC finances our purchase of software and services, which may include but are not limited to third party costs to design, install and implement software systems, and associated hardware described in the schedules defined within the Master IPA. The Master IPA was entered into to finance our implementation of a new enterprise resource planning (&#x201C;ERP&#x201D;) system, which began in October 2012 and is estimated to continue through early 2015. The terms of each note payable under the Master IPA consist of variable interest rates and payment terms based on amounts borrowed and timing of activity throughout the implementation of the ERP system.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">As of December 31, 2014 and </font><font style="display: inline;">2013, we had $</font><font style="display: inline;">11.6</font><font style="display: inline;"> million and </font><font style="display: inline;">$</font><font style="display: inline;">16.8</font><font style="display: inline;"> million</font><font style="display: inline;">, respectively, of long-term debt outstanding under </font><font style="display: inline;">five</font><font style="display: inline;"> separate notes payable, </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">of which </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">$5.3</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;"> million and </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">$5.1</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;"> million</font><font style="display: inline;">, respectively, represent current installments. As of December 31, 2014, the notes bear interest rates ranging from </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">2.45%</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;"> to </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">2.79%</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;">and maturities ranging from </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">September 2016</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;"> to </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">September 2017</font><font style="display: inline;">. As this debt arrangement relates solely to the construction and implementation of an ERP system for use by the entity, all interest expense incurred under the arrangement has been capitalized to the consolidated balance sheets until the assets are ready for intended use and will be amortized over the useful life of the software upon that date. During the years ended December 31, 2014 and 2013, we capitalized </font><font style="display: inline;">$0.4</font><font style="display: inline;"> million and </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">$0.3</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;"> million</font><font style="display: inline;">, respectively, in interest expense related to this</font><font style="display: inline;"> debt arrangement to the consolidated balance sheets. Interest rates and payment terms are subject to changes as further financing occurs under the Master IPA. </font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: DERIVATIVE FINANCIAL INSTRUMENTS</font><font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-size:10pt;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">We transact business in various foreign countries and are therefore exposed to foreign currency exchange rate risk inherent in revenues, costs, and monetary assets and liabilities denominated in non-functional currencies. We </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">have </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">enter</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">ed</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> into foreign currency exchange forward contract</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> and currency swap derivative instruments </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">to selectively protect against volatility in the value of non-functional currency denominated monetary assets and liabilities, and of future cash flows caused by changes in foreig</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">n currency exchange rates. We do not designate these</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">derivative instruments</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> as hedging instruments under the accounting standards for derivatives and hedging.</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> Accordingly, these instruments are recorded at fair value as a derivative asset or liability on the balance sheet with their corresponding change in fair value </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">recognized in &#x2018;Foreign currency transaction losses, net&#x2019; in our consolidated</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> statements of operations. For purposes of the cash flow statement, we classify</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> the cash flows at settlement from undesignated instruments in the same category as the cash flows from the related hedged </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">items, generally with</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">in &#x2018;Cash provided by operating activities</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">.</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">&#x2019; Se</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">e Note 7 &#x2014; Fair Value Measurements for further details regarding the fair values of the corresponding derivative assets and liabilities.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">The following table summarizes the notional amounts of the outstanding foreign cur</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">rency exchange contracts at </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">December 31, 2014 and 2013</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">. The notional amounts of the derivative financial instruments shown below</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> are denominated in their U.S. D</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">ollar equivalents and represent the amount of all contracts of the foreign currency specified. Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p><font size="1"> </font></p> </div> </div> <div> <div style="margin-left:0pt;margin-right:0pt;"> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> </p> <p><font size="1"> </font></p> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;;font-size: 10pt"><font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;"></font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;">Derivative Foreign Currency Contracts</font><font style="display: inline;">&#x2014;We are directly and indirectly affected by fluctuations in foreign currency rates which may adversely impact our financial performance. To mitigate the potential impact of foreign currency exchange rate risk, we may employ derivative financial instruments including forward contracts and option contracts. Forward contracts are agreements to buy or sell a quantity of a currency at a predetermined future date and at a predetermined rate. An option contract is an agreement that conveys the purchaser the right, but not the obligation, to buy or sell a quantity of a currency at a predetermined rate during a period or at a time in the future. These derivative financial instruments are viewed as risk management tools and are not used for trading or speculative purposes. We recognize derivative financial instruments as either assets or liabilities in the consolidated balance sheets and measure those instruments at fair value. Changes in the fair value of derivatives not designated or effective as hedges are recorded in &#x2018;Foreign currency transaction (gains)/losses, net&#x201D; in the consolidated statements of operations. We had no derivative instruments that qualified for hedge accounting during any of the periods presented. See Note&nbsp;7&#x2014;Fair Value Measurements and Financial Instruments for further discussion.</font> </p> <p><font size="1"> </font></p> </div> </div> <div> <div style="margin-left:0pt;margin-right:0pt;"> <p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">10. EQUITY</font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;">Equity Incentive Plans</font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">On August&nbsp;15, 2005, we adopted the 2005 Equity Incentive Plan (the &#x201C;2005 Plan&#x201D;), which permitted the issuance of up to </font><font style="display: inline;">14.0</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;million common shares in connection with the grant of non-qualified stock options, incentive stock options, and restricted stock to eligible employees, consultants and members of our Board. As of </font><font style="display: inline;">December 31, 2014 and 2013</font><font style="display: inline;">, &nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;">0.6</font><font style="display: inline;"> million and </font><font style="display: inline;">0.7</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;million stock options, respectively, were outstanding under the 2005 Plan. Following the adoption of the 2007 Equity Incentive Plan (the &#x201C;2007 Plan&#x201D;), described below, no additional grants were made under the 2005 Plan.</font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">On July 9, 2007, we adopted and on June 28, 2011 we amended, the 2007 Plan which increased the allowable number of shares of our common stock reserved for issuance under the 2007 Plan from </font><font style="display: inline;">9.0</font><font style="display: inline;"> million to </font><font style="display: inline;">15.3</font><font style="display: inline;"> million (subject to adjustment for future stock splits, stock dividends and similar changes in our capitalization) in connection with the grant of non-qualified stock options, incentive stock options, restricted stock, restricted stock units, stock appreciation rights, performance units, common stock or any other share-based award to eligible employees, consultants and members of our Board. shares were available for future issuance under the </font><font style="display: inline;">2007</font><font style="display: inline;"> Plan.</font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">Restricted stock awards and units generally vest annually on a straight-line basis over </font><font style="display: inline;">three</font><font The total grant date fair value of stock options vested during the years ended </font><font style="display: inline;">December 31, 2014, 2013 and 2012</font><font style="display: inline;"> was $</font><font style="display: inline;">0.8 </font><font style="display: inline;">million, $</font><font style="display: inline;">1.2</font><font style="display: inline;"> million, $</font><font style="display: inline;">2.8</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;million, respectively.</font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">As of </font><font style="display: inline;">December 31, 2014</font><font style="display: inline;">, we had $</font><font style="display: inline;">1.5</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;million of total unrecognized share-based compensation expense related to unvested options, net of expected forfeitures, which is expected to be amortized over the remaining weighted-average period of </font><font style="display: inline;">2.</font><font style="display: inline;">5</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;years.</font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">Stock options under both the 2005 Plan and the 2007 Plan generally vest ratably over </font><font style="display: inline;">four</font><font style="display: inline;"> years with the </font><font style="display: inline;">first</font><font style="display: inline;"> year vesting on a &#x201C;cliff&#x201D; basis followed by monthly vesting for the remaining </font><font style="display: inline;">three</font><font style="display: inline;"> years.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> </p> <p><font size="1"> </font></p> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;;font-size: 10pt"><font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;"></font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;font-size:10pt;">Restricted Stock Awards and Units </font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">From time to time, we grant restricted stock awards (RSAs) and restricted stock units (RSUs) to our employees. RSAs and RSUs generally vest over </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">three</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> or </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">four</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> years, depending on the terms of the grant. Unvested RSAs have the same rights as those of common shares including voting rights and non-forfeitable dividend rights. However, ownership of unvested RSAs cannot be transferred until they are vested. An unvested RSU is a contractual right to receive a share of common stock only upon its vesting. RSUs have dividend equivalent rights which accrue over the term of the award and are paid if and when the RSUs vest, but they have no voting rights.</font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt 0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">We typically grant time-based RSUs and performance-based RSUs. Time-based RSUs are typically granted on an annual basis to certain non-executive employees and vest in </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">three</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> annual installments on a straight-line basis beginning one year after the grant date. During the years ended December 31, 2014, 2013 and 2012, the Board approved grants of </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">0.3</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> million, </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">0.4</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> million and </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">0.4</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> million RSUs to certain non-executives. Performance-based RSUs are typically granted on an annual basis to certain executive employees and consist of a time-based and performance-based component. <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;color:#000000;">Separation Agreements</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;color:#000000;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">On December 27, 2013, John McCarvel resigned from his position as President, Chief Executive Officer (CEO) and director of the Company effective April 30, 2014. Also on December 27, 2013, the Company and Mr. McCarvel entered into a separation agreement providing that the Company will pay Mr. McCarvel (i) a </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">$1.1</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;"> million separation payment on the first regularly scheduled payroll date after the effectiveness of his resignation and (ii) a </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">$1.0</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;"> million separation payment on the first anniversary of the effectiveness of his resignation. In accordance with </font><font style="display: inline;font-style:italic;color:#000000;">ASC </font><font style="display: inline;font-style:italic;color:#000000;">420</font><font style="display: inline;font-style:italic;color:#000000;"> &#x2013; Exit or Disposal Cost Obligations</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">, the Company recognized the first and second installment payments of $1.1 million and $1.0 million ratably from December 27, 2013 through April 30, 2014. Mr. McCarvel was also entitled to receive any amount earned pursuant to the Company&#x2019;s 2013 annual incentive program, in such form and at such time as is provided under the terms of such program.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">Pursuant to the separation agreement, unvested share awards that vested through April 30, 2014 amounted to </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">58,840</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;"> shares. </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;color:#000000;">Additionally, pursuant to the terms of the separation agreement, Mr. McCarvel forfeited </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;color:#000000;">388,745</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;color:#000000;"> share awards which did not vest through April 30, 2014.</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;"> The separation payments are conditioned upon the effectiveness of Mr. McCarvel&#x2019;s release of claims in favor of the Company and his compliance with the non-competition, non-solicitation and confidentiality covenants contained in the separation agreement.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt;text-indent: -18pt;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;color:#000000;">On May 13, 2014, the Board appointed Andrew Rees as President of the Company with principal responsibilities for the Crocs brand, effective June 9, 2014. In addition, the Board appointed Mr. Rees as principal executive officer to serve until such time as the Board appoints a Chief Executive Officer of the Company, which it did effective January 28, 2015. Upon commencement of his employment, Mr. Rees was granted an RSU award representing to right to receive shares of our common stock equal to </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;color:#000000;">$197,534</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;color:#000000;">, based on the closing price of our common stock on the date immediately prior to his start date, which vests in </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;color:#000000;">three</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;color:#000000;"> annual installments beginning on the first anniversary of his start date, subject to his continued employment with us as of each vesting date. In addition, Mr. Rees was granted an RSU award representing the right to receive shares of our common stock equal to </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;color:#000000;">$3,500,000</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;color:#000000;">, based on a </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;color:#000000;">30</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;color:#000000;"> day weighted-average stock price as of May 13, 2014, and such RSU award shall vest based on achievement of certain share price levels before the fourth anniversary of his start date, subject to his continued employment with us. For calendar years after 2014, Mr. Rees is also eligible to participate in the Company&#x2019;s long-term incentive plan, with a target grant value of no less than </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;color:#000000;">$897,534</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;color:#000000;">.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt;text-indent: -18pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;font-size:10pt;color:#000000;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt;text-indent: -18pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;font-size:10pt;color:#000000;">Appointment of CEO</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt;text-indent: -18pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 12pt"> <font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;color:#000000;">On December 12, 2014, Gregg Ribatt was appointed our Chief Executive Officer, effective January 28, 2015.&nbsp;&nbsp;In connection with his appointment as Chief Executive Officer, Mr. Ribatt was granted a sign-on time-vesting RSU award representing the right to receive shares of our common stock equal to </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;color:#000000;">$2,000,000</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;color:#000000;">, based on a </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;color:#000000;">30</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;color:#000000;">-day weighted-average stock price as of December 15, 2014. This time-vesting RSU award will vest in three annual installments beginning on the first anniversary of his start date, subject to his continued employment with us as of each vesting date. In addition, Mr. Ribatt was granted a sign-on performance-vesting RSU award, subject to various vesting criteria, representing the right to receive shares of our common stock equal to </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;color:#000000;">$6,000,000</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;color:#000000;">, based on a </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;color:#000000;">30</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;color:#000000;">-day weighted-average stock price as of December 15, 2014. Based on a Monte-Carlo valuation model, the fair value of the RSU was determined to be </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;color:#000000;">$2.4</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;color:#000000;"> million, or </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;color:#000000;">46.0%</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;color:#000000;"> of the grant price, which will be expensed on a straight-line basis over a derived service period of </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;color:#000000;">2.5</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;color:#000000;"> years, beginning in 2015.</font> </p> <p><font size="1"> </font></p> </div> </div> 3067000 11301000 11301000 1.46 0.33 0.12 0.40 0.15 -0.76 0.06 -0.22 0.19 0.12 -0.70 1.44 0.33 0.12 0.40 0.15 -0.76 0.06 -0.22 0.19 0.12 -0.70 <div> <div style="margin-left:0pt;margin-right:0pt;"> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;">Earnings per Share</font><font style="display: inline;">&#x2014;</font><font style="display: inline;"> Basic and diluted earnings per common share (&#x201C;EPS&#x201D;) is presented using the two-class method, which is an earnings allocation formula that determines earnings per share for common stock and any participating securities according to dividend rights and participation rights in undistributed earnings. Under the two-class method, EPS is computed by dividing the sum of distributed and undistributed earnings attributable to common stockholders by the weighted-average number of shares of common stock outstanding during the period. A participating security is a security that may participate in undistributed earnings with common stock had those earnings been distributed in any form. Our recently issued Series A convertible preferred stock (&#x201C;Series A Preferred Stock&#x201D;) represents participating securities as holders of the Series A Preferred Stock are entitled to receive any and all dividends declared or paid on common stock on an as-converted basis. In addition, shares of our non-vested restricted stock awards are considered participating securities as they represent unvested share-based payment awards containing non-forfeitable rights to dividends. As such, these participating securities must be included in the computation of EPS pursuant to the two-class method on a pro-rata, as-converted basis. Diluted EPS reflects the potential dilution from securities that could share in our earnings. In addition, the dilutive effect of each participating security is calculated using the more dilutive of the two-class method described above, which assumes that the securities remain in their current form, or the if-converted method, which assumes conversion to common stock as of the beginning of the reporting date. Anti-dilutive securities are excluded from diluted EPS. See </font><font style="display: inline;">Note 13&#x2014;Earnings Per Share</font><font style="display: inline;"> for further discussion.</font> </p> <p><font size="1"> </font></p> </div> </div> <div> <div style="margin-left:0pt;margin-right:0pt;"> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">13. </table></div> <p style="margin:0pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt 6pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;">Non-Recurring Fair Value Measurements</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">The majority of our non-financial instruments, which include inventories, property and equipment and intangible assets, are not required to be carried at fair value on a recurring basis. However, if certain triggering events occur such that a non-financial instrument is required to be evaluated for impairment and the carrying value </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">is not recoverable, the carrying value would be adjusted to the lower of its cost or fair value and an impairment charge would be recorde</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">d. Se</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">e Note 2 &#x2013; Inventories, N</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">ote 3 &#x2013; Property and Equipment and Note 4 &#x2013; Goodwill &amp; Intangible Assets for discussions on impairment charges recorded during the periods presented.</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> </p> <p><font size="1"> </font></p> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;;font-size: 10pt"><font style="display: inline;"></font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 12pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p><font size="1"> </font></p> </div> </div> <div> <div style="margin-left:0pt;margin-right:0pt;"> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;font-size:10pt;">Fair Value</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">&#x2014;Fair value is the price that would be received from the sale of an asset or transfer of a liability in an orderly transaction between market participants at the measurement date. When determining the fair value measurements for assets and liabilities which are required to be recorded at fair value, we consider the principal or most advantageous market in which a hypothetical sale or transfer would take place and consider assumptions that market participants would use when pricing the asset or liability, such as inherent risk, transfer restrictions, and risk of non-performance.</font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">The fair value hierarchy is made up of three levels of inputs which may be used to measure fair value: </font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">Level&nbsp;1&#x2014;observable inputs such as quoted prices for identical instruments in active markets;</font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">Level&nbsp;2&#x2014;observable inputs such as quoted prices for similar instruments in active markets, quoted prices for identical or similar instruments in markets that are not active and model derived valuations in which all significant inputs are observable in active markets; and </font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">Level&nbsp;3&#x2014;unobservable inputs for which there is little or no market data and which require us to develop our own assumptions. We categorize fair value measurements within the fair value hierarchy based upon the lowest level of the most significant inputs used to determine such fair value measurement.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;color:#000000;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 12pt"> <font style="display: inline;color:#000000;font-size:10pt;">Cash equivalents primarily include time deposits and certificates of deposit with original maturities of three months or less. Time deposits and certificates of deposit included in cash equivalents are valued at amortized cost, which approximates fair value. These investments have been classified as a Level 1 measurement.</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">Derivative financial instruments are required to be recorded at their fair value, on a recurring basis. The fair values of </font><font style="display: inline;">any</font><font style="display: inline;"> derivative instruments</font><font style="display: inline;">, should we enter into them,</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;">would be</font><font style="display: inline;"> determined using a discounted cash flow valuation model. The significant inputs used in the model are readily available in public markets or can be derived from observable market transactions, and therefore, have been classified as Level&nbsp;2. These inputs include the applicable exchange rates and forward rates, and discount rates based on the prevailing LIBOR deposit rates.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> </p> <p><font size="1"> </font></p> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;;font-size: 10pt"><font style="display: inline;"></font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">Our other financial instruments are not required to be carried at fair value on a recurring basis. The carrying value of these financial instruments, including cash equivalents, accounts receivable, accounts payable and accrued liabilities, approximates fair value due to their short maturities. Based on borrowing rates currently available to us, with similar terms, the carrying values of capital lease obligations and the line of credit approximate their fair values.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">Inventories and long-lived assets such as property and equipment and intangible assets are also not required to be carried at fair value on a recurring basis. For a discussion of inventory estimated fair value see &#x201C;Inventory Valuation&#x201D; below. However, when determining impairment losses, the fair values of property and equipment and intangibles must be determined. For such determination, we generally use either an income approach with inputs that are mainly unobservable, such as expected future cash flows, or a market approach using observable inputs such as replacement cost or third-party appraisals, as appropriate. Estimated future cash flows are based on management&#x2019;s operating budgets and forecasts which take into consideration both observable and unobservable inputs including growth rates, pricing, new markets and other factors expected to affect the business, as well as management&#x2019;s forecasts for inventory, receivables, capital spending, and other cash needs.</font><font style="display: inline;"> We consider this type of estimate to be classified as a Level 3 measurement. </font><font style="display: inline;">See Note&nbsp;7&#x2014;Fair Value Measurements for further discussion related to fair value measurements.</font> </p> <p><font size="1"> </font></p> </div> </div> 65633000 4548000 4272000 49665000 6439000 709000 78126000 4170000 4931000 62591000 5798000 636000 20427000 20198000 10844000 12334000 13825000 19376000 137850000 4548000 6501000 118940000 6878000 983000 175130000 4170000 6702000 157615000 5945000 698000 72217000 2229000 69275000 439000 274000 97004000 1771000 95024000 147000 62000 P7Y P10Y P5Y 13501000 13501000 984000 984000 -2500000 -4678000 -4885000 -13928000 6420000 11100000 <div> <div style="margin-left:0pt;margin-right:0pt;"> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;">Foreign Currency Translation and Foreign Currency Transactions</font><font style="display: inline;">&#x2014;Our </font><font style="display: inline;">reporting currency is the U.S. D</font><font style="display: inline;">ollar. Assets and liabilities of foreign operations denominated in local currencies are translated at the rate of exchange at the balance sheet date. Revenues and expenses are translated at the weighted-average rate of exchange during the applicable period. </table></div> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;">Goodwill Impairment</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">We assess goodwill for impairment on an annual basis on the last day of the fourth quarter, or more frequently if events and circumstances indicate impairment may have occurred, at the reporting unit level. If the carrying value of the goodwill exceeds its implied fair value, we record an impairment loss equal to the difference. During the year ended December 31, 201</font><font style="display: inline;">3</font><font style="display: inline;">, we recorded </font><font style="display: inline;">$0.3</font><font style="display: inline;"> million of</font><font style="display: inline;"> goodwill impairment related to </font><font style="display: inline;">the retail channel</font><font style="display: inline;"> of our Crocs Benelux B.V. business purchased by our Crocs Stores B.V. subsidiary in July 2012. Goodwill and associated impairments are part of our Europe operating segment. During the years ended December 31, 201</font><font style="display: inline;">4</font><font style="display: inline;"> and 201</font><font style="display: inline;">2</font><font style="display: inline;">, we did </font><font style="display: inline;">not</font><font style="display: inline;"> record any impairments related to goodwill.</font> </p> <p><font size="1"> </font></p> </div> </div> <div> <div style="margin-left:0pt;margin-right:0pt;"> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;font-size:10pt;">Intangible Assets</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">&#x2014;Intangible assets that are determined to have finite lives are amortized over their useful lives on a straight-line basis. Customer relationships are amortized on a straight-line basis or an accelerated basis. Indefinite lived intangible assets, such as trade names, are not amortized and are evaluated for impairment at least annually and when circumstances imply possible impairment. </font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">Amortization of manufacturing intangible assets is included in cost of sales on the consolidated statements of operations. Amortization related to corporate, non-product and non-manufacturing assets such as our global information systems is included in selling, general and administrative expenses on the consolidated statements of operations. The following table sets forth our definite lived intangible assets and the periods over which they are amortized.</font> </p> <div style="width:100%"><table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" align="center" style="border-collapse:collapse;width: 75.00%;margin-left:0pt;"> <tr> <td valign="bottom" style="width:215.00pt;padding:0pt 4.3pt;"> <p style="margin:0pt 0pt 1pt;border-bottom:1pt solid #000000 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 8pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-size:8pt;">Intangible Asset Class</font></p> </td> <td valign="bottom" style="width:195.40pt;padding:0pt 4.3pt;"> <p style="margin:0pt 0pt 1pt;border-bottom:1pt solid #000000 ;text-align:center;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 8pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-size:8pt;">Weighted-average Amortization Period</font></p> </td> </tr> <tr> <td valign="top" style="width:215.00pt;padding:0pt 4.3pt;"> <p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10pt;text-indent: -10pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="text-indent:0pt;margin-left:-10pt; overflow: hidden; white-space: nowrap;"><font style="display: inline;">Customer relationships</font>.........................................</font><font style="text-indent:0pt;margin-left:0pt;text-align:right"><font style="display: inline;"></font></font></p> </td> <td valign="bottom" style="width:195.40pt;padding:0pt 4.3pt;"> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">Estimated customer life</font></p> </td> </tr> <tr> <td valign="top" style="width:215.00pt;padding:0pt 4.3pt;"> <p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10pt;text-indent: -10pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="text-indent:0pt;margin-left:-10pt; overflow: hidden; white-space: nowrap;"><font style="display: inline;">Core technology</font>...................................................</font><font style="text-indent:0pt;margin-left:0pt;text-align:right"><font style="display: inline;"></font></font></p> </td> <td valign="bottom" style="width:195.40pt;padding:0pt 4.3pt;"> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">5</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;years</font></p> </td> </tr> <tr> <td valign="top" style="width:215.00pt;padding:0pt 4.3pt;"> <p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10pt;text-indent: -10pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="text-indent:0pt;margin-left:-10pt; overflow: hidden; white-space: nowrap;"><font style="display: inline;">Non-competition agreement</font>...................................</font><font style="text-indent:0pt;margin-left:0pt;text-align:right"><font style="display: inline;"></font></font></p> </td> <td valign="bottom" style="width:195.40pt;padding:0pt 4.3pt;"> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">Contractual term</font></p> </td> </tr> <tr> <td valign="top" style="width:215.00pt;padding:0pt 4.3pt;"> <p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10pt;text-indent: -10pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="text-indent:0pt;margin-left:-10pt; overflow: hidden; white-space: nowrap;"><font style="display: inline;">Capitalized software</font>.............................................</font><font style="text-indent:0pt;margin-left:0pt;text-align:right"><font style="display: inline;"></font></font></p> </td> <td valign="bottom" style="width:195.40pt;padding:0pt 4.3pt;"> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">Shorter of </font><font style="display: inline;">7</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;years or useful life</font></p> </td> </tr> </table></div> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 31.5pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-style:italic;">Capitalized Software</font><font style="display: inline;">&#x2014;We capitalize certain internal and external software acquisition and development costs, including the costs of employees and contractors devoting time to the software development projects and external direct costs for materials and services. Initial costs associated with internally-developed-and-used software are expensed until it is determined that the project has reached the application development stage. Once in its development stage, subsequent additions, modifications or upgrades to an internal-use software project are capitalized to the extent that they add functionality. Software maintenance and training costs are expensed in the period in which they are incurred. Capitalized software primarily consists of our enterprise resource system software, warehouse management software and point of sale software. At least annually, we consider the potential impairment of capitalized software by assessing the substantive service potential of the software, changes, if any, in the extent or manner in which the software is used or is expected to be used, and the actual cost of software development or modification compared to expected cost. See Note&nbsp;4&#x2014;Goodwill and Intangible Assets for further discussion.</font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 31.5pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-style:italic;">Impairment of Intangible Assets</font><font style="display: inline;">&#x2014;Intangible assets with indefinite lives are evaluated for impairment when events or changes in circumstances indicate that the carrying value may not be fully recoverable and at least annually. Intangible assets that are determined to have definite lives are amortized over their useful lives and are evaluated for impairment only when events or circumstances indicate a carrying value may not be fully recoverable. Recoverability is based on the estimated future undiscounted cash flows of the asset. If the asset is not supported on an undiscounted cash flow basis, the amount of impairment is measured as the difference between its carrying value and its estimated fair value.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;">Goodwill</font><font style="display: inline;">&#x2014;</font><font style="display: inline;">Goodwill</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;"> represents the excess purchase price paid over the fair value of assets acquired and liabilities assumed in acquisitions</font><font style="display: inline;">. Goodwill is considered an indefinite lived asset and therefore is not amortized.&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;">The Company assesses goodwill for impairment annually on the last day of the fourth quarter, or more frequently if events and circumstances indicate impairment may have occurred. If the carrying value of goodwill exceeds its implied fair value, the Company records an impairment loss equal to the difference. See </font><font style="display: inline;">Note&nbsp;4&#x2014;Goodwill</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;"> and Intangible Assets for discussion of goodwill balances and </font><font style="display: inline;">discussion of impairment losses recorded during the periods presented</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;">.</font> </p> <p><font size="1"> </font></p> </div> </div> 2508000 2044000 0 300000 300000 0 607977000 165849000 623198000 200867000 153581000 102901000 156227000 590345000 202571000 155017000 76530000 1410000 1410000 10611000 3861000 185000 6565000 10400000 8827000 4001000 2807000 2019000 <div> <div style="margin-left:0pt;margin-right:0pt;"> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;">Impairment of Long-Lived Assets</font><font style="display: inline;">&#x2014;Long-lived assets to be held and used are evaluated for impairment when events or circumstances indicate the carrying value of a long-lived asset may not be fully recoverable. Events that may indicate the impairment of a long-lived asset (or asset group, as defined below) include (i)&nbsp;a significant decrease in its market price, (ii)&nbsp;a significant adverse change in the extent or manner in which it is being used or in its physical condition, (iii)&nbsp;a significant adverse change in legal factors or business climate that could affect its value, including an adverse action or assessment by a regulator, (iv)&nbsp;an accumulation of costs significantly in excess of the amount originally expected for its acquisition or construction, (v)&nbsp;its current period operating or cash flow losses combined with historical operating or cash flow losses or a forecast of its cash flows demonstrate continuing losses associated with its use, and (vi)&nbsp;a current expectation that, more likely than not, it will be sold or otherwise disposed of significantly before the end of its previously estimated useful life. If such facts indicate a potential impairment of a long-lived asset (or asset group), we assess the recoverability by determining if its carrying value exceeds the sum of its projected undiscounted cash flows from its use and eventual disposition over its remaining economic life. If the asset is not supported on an undiscounted cash flow basis, the amount of impairment is measured as the difference between its carrying value and its estimated fair value. Assets held for sale are reported at the lower of the carrying amount or fair value less costs to sell. Assets to be abandoned or from which no further benefit is expected are written down to zero at the time that the determination is made and the assets are removed entirely from service.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">An asset group is the lowest level of assets and liabilities for which identifiable cash flows are largely independent of the cash flows of other assets and liabilities. For assets involved in our retail business, our asset group is at the retail store level. See Note 3 &#x2013; Property and Equipment for a discussion of impairment losses recorded during the periods presented.</font> </p> <p><font size="1"> </font></p> </div> </div> 12060000 -7818000 -34622000 133488000 67777000 26073000 145548000 59959000 -8549000 <div> <div style="margin-left:0pt;margin-right:0pt;"> <p style="margin:0pt 0pt 15pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">1</font><font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">2</font><font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">.
